<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="188" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1728,2010]" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,286,1728,1753]" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is derived from the Latin 
<emphasis box="[803,886,1728,1752]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">pumilis</emphasis>
, dwarfish, little, and alludes to the minute size of the specimens.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,560,1800,1825]" pageId="1" pageNumber="188" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1728,2010]" box="[199,560,1800,1825]" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1800,1825]" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
As that of the genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="188" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1728,2010]" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,506,1836,1861]" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">Ecology and distribution.</emphasis>
Specimens are known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[940,988,1837,1861]" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">type</typeStatus>
locality, Barro Colorado Island, where they were found in a large pile of humid leaf mulch accumulated between two buttress roots of an old broadleaf tree.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
